It would seem the National Lotteries Commission (NLC) has run out of luck, with authorities knocking at the door. The Special Investigating Unit and the Hawks searched its head office in Pretoria on Tuesday. The NLC has been the subject of numerous allegations of corruption. Barry Bateman reports. Courtesy #DStv403 PRETORIA - It would seem the National Lotteries Commission (NLC) has run out of luck, with authorities knocking at the door. The Special Investigating Unit (SIU) and the Hawks searched its head office in Pretoria on Tuesday. The NLC has been the subject of numerous allegations of corruption. READ: SIU raids National Lotteries offices It's alleged senior officials colluded with friends and relatives to secure grants worth millions of rand. "We must look at maladministration in the commission," said SIU spokesperson Kaizer Kganyago. "We must also look at whether... the dispensement of this fund has been done in accordance with the law." The commission says it's cooperating with the investigators. READ: Alleged corruption probed at National Lotteries Commission It also says it has sufficient mechanisms in place to identify and deal with corruption. "We welcome the checks and balances of the state, even through the SIU so that maybe it will put this matter to rest," said Ndivhuho Mafela, NLC spokesperson. The evidence gathered on Tuesday will be analysed and if there is a case, it will be handed over to the Hawks for further investigation. * eNCA's Barry Bateman reports.